    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-05-20T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-05-20T10:00:00-05:00" n="480"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d480">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">859.01/167: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bucknell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-05-20T17:00:00+02:00"
                            >May 20, 1944—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 8:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4079. Reference Embassy’s 3892, May 13, 2 p.m.<note n="30" xml:id="d480fn30">Not
                        printed.</note> A communication has been received from the Foreign Office
                    stating that a telegram has now been received from Moscow to the effect that the
                    British Ambassador sent the draft declaration on Denmark to M. Vyshinski<note
                        n="31" xml:id="d480fn31">Andrey Yanuaryevich Vyshinsky, First Assistant
                        People’s Commissar for Foreign Affairs of the Soviet Union.</note> on May 9.
                    In accordance with an arrangement with the American Chargé, who wrote Vyshinski
                    May 10, the British Ambassador’s letter <pb facs="0549" n="537" xml:id="pg_537"
                    /> made no mention of the prior clearance of the declaration with the King of
                    Denmark.</p>
                <p>As a result of further telegrams from the F.O. regarding proposed arrangements
                    for publication, the British Ambassador has again written to M. Vyshinski
                    stressing the urgency of the matter and he proposes to remind the Soviets
                    again.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Moscow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bucknell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
